    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d26eebea_b25b44eb",
        "filename": "gen_syscalls-inl.h",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 14,
      "author": {
        "id": 1293738
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-08-25T02:07:30Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The idea here was for \"#else\" to be the architectures using asm-generic (which is a quite a few, including arm64), but it\u0027s true that 32-bit ARM does not use asm-generic and it\u0027s missing here. Would you prefer to just not define it for the \"generic\" architectures?",
      "parentUuid": "aad46f31_f96b1a73",
      "revId": "c71312c1025cdbdda97f4c61c9c86c5c397dbd66",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "46b98902_11a1f5b2",
        "filename": "gen_syscalls-inl.h",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 14,
      "author": {
        "id": 1040868
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-08-25T02:22:53Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "even asm-generic arches are messy with some syscalls when it comes to compat symbols.  i\u0027m reluctant to start relying on that pattern and then having to remember whether it\u0027s a \"safe\" symbol.  see the stat and related symbols.\n\nif that weren\u0027t a problem, i\u0027m not sure there\u0027s an easy way to determine whether the current target is an asm-generic arch.  we could sniff header defines but i really like to avoid those :/.",
      "parentUuid": "d26eebea_b25b44eb",
      "revId": "c71312c1025cdbdda97f4c61c9c86c5c397dbd66",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
